Once an attacker has one foothold and stolen credentials (see Detection 2), they need to spread. PsExec (a legitimate Sysinternals admin tool) is the single most abused "living off the land" tool for lateral movement — it lets you run commands on remote machines using stolen admin credentials, and because it's a real, signed Microsoft tool, plain antivirus often won't flag it. Same story for wmic ... process call create (remote process creation via WMI) and sc.exe create (creating a remote service to execute code) — these are all textbook Ransomware pre-deployment steps (attackers "spray" the ransomware binary to every machine on the network this way, right before detonation).